# Shared Environment Variables for Ohouse AI Monorepo
# ========================================================
#
# This file documents shared API keys and configuration that all projects
# in the monorepo can access. Each project can either use these shared keys
# or override with project-specific values in their own .env.local
#
# DO NOT COMMIT .env.local files - they contain sensitive API keys
# Only .env.example files (templates) should be committed to git

# OpenAI API Integration
# Used by: ai-consultant, ohouse-ai-app, and other projects
# Format: Bearer token from OpenAI platform
# Get your key: https://platform.openai.com/account/api-keys
OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-proj-your_openai_api_key_here

# Nano Bananas Image Generation API
# Used by: projects with AI image generation features
# Format: API key for nano bananas service
NANO_BANANAS_API_KEY=your_nano_bananas_api_key_here

# Project-Specific Configuration (Override per project as needed)
# ================================================================

# Next.js Environment
NODE_ENV=development

# Example: Port configuration (can be overridden per project)
# NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:3000

# ========================================================
# IMPORTANT NOTES FOR DEVELOPERS
# ========================================================
#
# 1. API KEY SHARING ACROSS PROJECTS:
#    - Set keys once in root .env file
#    - All projects can access via process.env.OPENAI_API_KEY
#    - Each project's .env.local inherits these values
#    - Override: Add the same key to project/.env.local for project-specific value
#
# 2. ENVIRONMENT SETUP:
#    - Copy this file to .env.local at the root
#    - Add your actual API keys to .env.local
#    - Never commit .env.local (it's in .gitignore)
#    - Each project also has its own .env.example for project-specific vars
#
# 3. WHICH .env FILE TO USE:
#    - Use root .env for SHARED API keys (OpenAI, Nano Bananas, etc.)
#    - Use project/.env.local for PROJECT-SPECIFIC configuration
#    - Root .env values are inherited by all projects automatically
#
# 4. HOW TO ACCESS IN CODE:
#    - In Next.js API routes: const apiKey = process.env.OPENAI_API_KEY;
#    - In Next.js client (public): Use NEXT_PUBLIC_* prefix
#    - In Vercel deployment: Add same keys to Vercel environment settings
#
# 5. SECURITY:
#    - Rotate API keys regularly
#    - Use service accounts or restricted keys when possible
#    - Monitor API usage in respective platforms
#    - Never share .env.local files via email or chat
